Edwin  Irabor', 'FF9DEDE3');
There was not a single old man or old woman in the village.', NULL);
Very soon, they forgot how to work.', NULL);
The young men and women of Izagodo woke up one day and all the food was finished. There was not a drop of wine left. The musical instruments were all broken.', NULL);
They went to the compound of Oza, the village chief, and cried bitterly.', NULL);
The young chief came out of his large hut and pleaded, "Stop! Dear people of Izagodo. Please stop crying. We might die soon, let us save our strength for a few more breaths."', NULL);
Chief Oza was quiet. Then after a while, he stood up and said, "I am no longer your chief. I shall leave this village and find somewhere peaceful. You can choose another chief."', NULL);
The people did not know who would be their leader. They did not know what to do. They cried so much more.', NULL);
Everybody turned to look for the owner of the voice. They all looked to each other. They looked and looked. But they could not tell who had spoken.', NULL);
The boy said, "Yes! I will be chief. I can help you. But you must promise to stop having fun all day and all night. And you must follow my advice."', NULL);
He took them away from the village, to a lush farm. They had food and rested. Then he taught them. He helped them to remember how to farm.', NULL);
Before long, they had more than enough to eat and drink. They were happy again and had fun. But also they continued to work.', NULL);
He told him moonlight tales, and stories of great men and women who solved the problems of their people.
In time, the boy himself became a wise and powerful man.', NULL);
